        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1540271964,
        "creation_date": 1540271964,
        "body": "<p><code>DateTimeException<\/code> is an unchecked exception, so it doesn't have to be declared methods.<\/p>\n\n<p>Why does <code>LocalDate#format<\/code> declare it? Because it can be thrown by methods it itself delegates that execution to. Following the call chain, we see that <code>DateTimeFormatter.formatTo(TemporalAccessor, Appendable)<\/code> is the method doing the actual work, and it is throwing the exception; and none of the intermediate methods is catching/handling it.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public void formatTo(TemporalAccessor temporal, Appendable appendable) {\n    ...\n    try {\n        ...\n    } catch (IOException ex) {\n        throw new DateTimeException(ex.getMessage(), ex);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I believe this is indeed an example of good exception documentation (document exceptions that should be expected, be they checked or not, even if you are not explicitly throwing them in the method in question)<\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 52941644,
        "question_id": 52941548
    }],
